<subSubSection id="CAAE6535FFC6FFADFF7BFB34FB73FAC9" pageId="122" pageNumber="123" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="820B36BEFFC6FFADFF7BFB34FE82FAB9" blockId="122.[189,303,1256,1282]" box="[189,303,1256,1282]" pageId="122" pageNumber="123">
<heading id="D94381D2FFC6FFADFF7BFB34FE82FAB9" bold="true" box="[189,303,1256,1282]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="122" pageNumber="123" reason="3">
<emphasis id="B0C0EAACFFC6FFADFF7BFB34FE82FAB9" bold="true" box="[189,303,1256,1282]" pageId="122" pageNumber="123">Remarks</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="820B36BEFFC6FFADFF7BFAC9FB73FAC9" blockId="122.[189,1398,1301,1395]" pageId="122" pageNumber="123">
The lack of males from the northern part of the distribution area of this species was interpreted by 
<bibRefCitation id="E6254B4FFFC6FFADFF7BFAEBFED4FAEA" author="Verhoeff K. W." box="[189,377,1335,1361]" pageId="122" pageNumber="123" pagination="1 - 110" refId="ref40464" refString="Verhoeff K. W. 1921. Uber Diplopoden der Riviera und einige alpenlandische Chilognathan (92. Diplopoden-Aufsatz). Archiv fur Naturgeschichte 87 A (2): 1 - 110." type="journal article" year="1921">Verhoeff (1921)</bibRefCitation>
as “klimatisch-geographisches Parthenogenese”. This seems to have been the first time that the phenomenon “geographical parthenogenesis” was recognized (see 
<bibRefCitation id="E6254B4FFFC6FFADFBEDFA84FB7CFAC9" author="Enghoff H." box="[1067,1233,1368,1394]" pageId="122" pageNumber="123" pagination="25 - 31" refId="ref34808" refString="Enghoff H. 1994. Geographical parthenogenesis in millipedes. Biogeographica 70 (1): 25 - 31." type="journal article" year="1994">Enghoff 1994</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
